            <section class="prose mt-10">
              <h2>How this calorie calculator works</h2>
              <p>
                This tool uses the <strong>Mifflin-St Jeor</strong> formula, considered one of the most accurate for estimating basal metabolic rate (BMR), and applies an <strong>activity factor</strong> to obtain total daily energy expenditure (TDEE).
              </p>

              <div class="formula-box">
                <p class="font-semibold mb-1">Mifflin-St Jeor formula</p>
                <p class="mb-1">
                  <strong>Men:</strong> \( BMR = 10 \cdot weight(kg) + 6{,}25
                  \cdot height(cm) - 5 \cdot age(years) + 5 \)
                </p>
                <p class="mb-1">
                  <strong>Women:</strong> \( BMR = 10 \cdot weight(kg) + 6{,}25
                  \cdot height(cm) - 5 \cdot age(years) - 161 \)
                </p>
                <p class="mt-2 mb-1">
                  <strong>TDEE:</strong> \( TDEE = BMR \times activity\_factor
                  \)
                </p>
                <ul class="mb-0">
                  <li>Sedentary: 1.2</li>
                  <li>Lightly active: 1.375</li>
                  <li>Moderately active: 1.55</li>
                  <li>Very active: 1.725</li>
                  <li>Extremely active: 1.9</li>
                </ul>
              </div>

              <h3>Calorie deficit and surplus</h3>
              <p>
                To lose or gain weight, you adjust the <strong>offset from TDEE</strong>:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Weight loss:</strong> a deficit of about 300-500 kcal/day relative to TDEE.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Weight gain/mass:</strong> a surplus of about 200-400 kcal/day relative to TDEE.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                The calculator translates your goal into a deficit/surplus aligned with the chosen rate of weight change, using a reference of about <strong>7,700 kcal per 1 kg of fat</strong>.
              </p>

              <h2>Worked example</h2>
              <p>
                Assume a 35-year-old woman, 65 kg, 165 cm, moderately active (3-5 workouts/week), who wants to lose 0.5 kg per week.
              </p>
              <ol>
                <li>BMR calculation: about 1,380 kcal/day.</li>
                <li>TDEE = 1,380 x 1.55 ≈ 2,140 kcal/day.</li>
                <li>
                  To lose 0.5 kg/week you need about 3,850 kcal of deficit per week, or ~550 kcal/day.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Recommended calories ≈ 2,140 - 550 = 1,590 kcal/day (approx. range 1,550-1,650).
                </li>
              </ol>

              <h2>Limits and cautions</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Formulas provide <strong>estimates</strong>, not direct measurements of your metabolism.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Avoid dropping below <strong>1,200 kcal/day for women</strong> and <strong>1,400 kcal/day for men</strong> without medical supervision.
                </li>
                <li>
                  If you have <strong>medical conditions, pregnancy, breastfeeding, or eating disorders</strong>, consult a doctor or dietitian.
                </li>
              </ul>
            </section>

            <section class="prose mt-10">
              <h2>Calorie FAQ</h2>

              <h3>How many calories should I eat per day to lose weight?</h3>
              <p>
                A prudent strategy is to create a deficit of <strong>300-500 kcal</strong> per day relative to your TDEE. The calculator shows a recommended range based on your chosen rate of weight loss.
              </p>

              <h3>How many calories do I need to gain weight or muscle?</h3>
              <p>
                To gain weight in a controlled way, a surplus of <strong>200-400 kcal</strong> per day over TDEE is typical. For lifting and muscle gain, many use an extra <strong>250-350 kcal</strong> with protein at 1.6-2.2 g/kg of body weight.
              </p>

              <h3>Why is my weight not changing even if I track calories?</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Fluid fluctuations (salt, menstrual cycle, stress, sleep).
                </li>
                <li>Portion or food estimates that are off.</li>
                <li>
                  Daily movement (NEAT) that unconsciously drops during dieting.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                Evaluate progress over at least <strong>2-3 weeks</strong> and, if needed, adjust by 100-150 kcal.
              </p>

              <h3>Is it better to count calories or follow hunger cues?</h3>
              <p>
                It depends. Calorie counting is a useful tool to understand needs and portions, but it is not required forever. It can be used for an educational period and then transition to a more intuitive approach based on hunger and satiety.
              </p>

              <h3>Do I need to calculate macronutrients too?</h3>
              <p>
                For many goals, meeting calorie targets and adequate protein is enough. However, for athletic performance, body recomposition, or specific clinical conditions, it can help to customize <strong>carbohydrates, fats, and protein</strong>.
              </p>
